      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5978"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>IL-15 receptor alpha is a subchain of the IL-15 receptor.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="950" y="83" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL2RB" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6009"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>IL-2 receptor beta is a subchain of the IL-2 and IL-15 receptors.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1030" y="113" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL2RA" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(SMAD3 | FOXP3 | STAT5 | NFKB) &amp; NFAT"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6008"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>IL-2 receptor alpha (CD25) is a subchain of the IL-2 receptor. 

Activated by NFKB, NFAT and Stat5: functional and binding data in Kim et al. (2006).

Activated by Smad3 and Foxp3: functional data in Kim et al. (2006).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1117" y="102" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL27RA" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:17290"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>IL-27 receptor alpha is a subchain of the IL-27 receptor.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="266" y="129" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL1R1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="STAT3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5993"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>IL1R1 is a subchain of IL-1 receptor.

We assume that Stat3 inhibits IL1R1 in order to account for ILR1 differential expression in naive Th and Th17 cells (Vigne et al., 2012, Fig 1B).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="16" y="90" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL29R" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IL29_e &amp; IL28RA &amp; IL10RB"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <comment>Activated by its subchain(s) and by its associated cytokine(s) (external or secreted).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1525" y="173" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL17RB" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:18015"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Receptor of the cytokine IL-25.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1403" y="94" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL18RAP" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5989"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>IL18RAP is a subchain of the IL-18 receptor.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1474" y="91" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL18RA" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5988"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>IL18RA (IL18R1) is a subchain of the IL-18 receptor. </comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1484" y="121" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL18R" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IL18_e &amp; IL18RAP &amp; IL18RA &amp; STAT4"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <comment>Activated by its subchain(s) and by its associated cytokine(s) (external or secreted).

Activated by Stat4: functional data in Nakahira et al. (2001) (Fig 4); binding data in Yu et al. (2007) (Fig 5C).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1430" y="175" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="ST2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="GATA3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11347"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>ST2 is a subchain of the IL-33 receptor. </comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1334" y="93" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL25R" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IL17RB &amp; (IL25_e | IL25)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <comment>Activated by its subchain(s) and by its associated cytokine(s) (external or secreted).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1373" y="176" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL33R" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IL33_e &amp; ST2 &amp; IL1RAP"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <comment>Activated by its subchain(s) and by its associated cytokine(s) (external or secreted).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1304" y="177" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL1RL2" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5999"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>IL-1RL2 is a suchain of the IL-36 receptor.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1631" y="94" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL28RA" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:18584"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>IL28RA is a subchain of the IL-29 receptor.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1560" y="95" style="Node style 8"/>
    </node>
    <node id="TBET" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(TBET | STAT1 | IL36R) &amp; !BCL6 &amp; !RORGT"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11599"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor T-bet.

T-bet is the master regulator of Th1 lineage.

Auto-activated: binding and functional data in Kanhere et al. (2012) (Fig 5).

Activated by STAT1: functional data in Afkarian et al. (2002) (Fig 2).

Activated by IL36R: functional data in Vigne et al. (2012) (Fig 2C).

Inhibited by RORGT: functional data in Mukasa et al. (2010) (Fig S5B).

Inhibited by BCL6: binding and functional data in Yu et al. (2009) (Fig 4).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="153" y="692" style="Node style 17"/>
    </node>
    <node id="GATA3" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!GATA3 &amp; !TBET &amp; (STAT6 | IL25R) &amp; !BCL6 &amp; !PU1 &amp; !IL29R"/>
        <exp str="GATA3 &amp; !BCL6 &amp; !PU1 &amp; !IL29R"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:4172"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Gata3.

Gata3 is the master regulator of Th2 lineage.

Activated by Stat6: functional data in Ouyang et al. (1998) (Fig 1C). 

Activated by Gata3: functional data in Ouyang et al. (2000) (Fig 6A). 

Activated by IL25R: functional data in Wang et al. (2007) (Fig 4).

Inhibited by Tbet: binding and functional data in Usui et al. (2006) (Fig 5) and Hwang et al. (2005b) (Fig 3).

Inhibited by IL29R: functional data in Dai et al. (2009) (Fig 5).

Inhibited by Bcl6: functional data in Nurieva et al. (2009) (Fig S2C).

Inhibited by PU.1: binding and functional data in Chang et al. (2005) (Fig 6,7).

Gata3 is auto-activated and activated by IL25R and STAT6, and inhibited by TBET, IL29R, PU1 and BCL6.

Tbet overexpression inhibits Gata3 expression (Usui et al., 2006, PMID 16520391). Tbet interacts with Gata3 and sequesters it away from binding to target DNA (Hwang et al., 2005, PMID 15662016; Kanhere et al., Nat Com, 2012, PMID 23232398).

</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="422" y="697" style="Node style 17"/>
    </node>
    <node id="RORGT" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="TGFBR &amp; STAT3 &amp; !BCL6 &amp; !FOXP3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:10260"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Rorgammat.

Rorgammat is the main transcription factor of Th17 lineage.

Activated by STAT3: functional data in Laurence et al. (2007) (Fig 4C).

Activated by TGFBR: functional data in Ivanov et al. (2006) (Fig 3C).

Inhibited by BCL6: binding data in Yu et al. (2009) (Fig 4A); functional data in Nurieva et al. (2009) (Fig 3C).

Inhibited by FOXP3: binding and functional data in Zhou et al. (2008) (Fig 3).

According to (Zhou et al, 2007, Fig.2C and 3C), TGFb or IL6 alone does not activate RORgt. Moreover, IL6R activates Stat3. This suggests a synergic activation of RORgt by STAT3 and TGFBR.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="547" y="706" style="Node style 17"/>
    </node>
    <node id="FOXP3" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="STAT5 &amp; NFAT &amp; FOXP3 &amp; !STAT6"/>
        <exp str="STAT5 &amp; NFAT &amp; !FOXP3 &amp; SMAD3 &amp; !STAT1 &amp; !(STAT3 &amp; RORGT) &amp; !STAT6"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6106"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Foxp3.

Foxp3 is the master regulator of Treg lineage.

Auto-activated: binding and functional data in Zheng et al. (2010) (Fig 4).

Activated by STAT5: binding and functional data in Yao et al. (2007) (Fig 6A and 7): functional data in Jenks et al. (2013) (Fig 2D). 

Activated by NFAT and SMAD3: binding and functional data in Tone et al. (2008) (Fig 4, 6 and 7).

Inhibited by RORGT: binding and functional data in Burgler et al. (2010) (Fig 1, 2, 4 and 5).

Inhibited by STAT6: functional data in Dardalhon et al. (2008) (Fig 2B and 2C).
 
Inhibited by STAT3: functional data in Laurence et al. (2012) (Fig 5A).

We assume that Stat1 inhibits Foxp3 (putative binding data in Floess et al. (2007) (Fig. S1)).




</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="716" y="703" style="Node style 17"/>
    </node>
    <node id="BCL6" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(STAT1 | STAT3 | STAT4) &amp; !TBET &amp; !STAT5"/>
        <exp str="STAT3 &amp; STAT4 &amp; !TBET"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:1001"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Bcl6.

Bcl6 is the master regulator of Tfh lineage.

Activated by STAT1: functional data in Choi et al. (2013) (Fig 3 and 4).

Activated by STAT4: functional data in Nakayamada et al. (2011) (Fig 2E).

Activated by STAT3: functional data in Choi et al. (2013) (Fig 2 and 3).

Inhibited by TBET: functional data in Nakayamada et al. (2011) (Fig 4D).

Inhibited by STAT5: functional data in Johnston et al. (2012) (Fig 2).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1143" y="689" style="Node style 17"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IFNG" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="proliferation &amp; !FOXP3 &amp; NFAT &amp; ((TBET &amp; RUNX3) | STAT4 | IL18R)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5438"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interferon gamma.

Interferon gamma is produced by Th1 cells. 

Activated by TBET and Runx3: binding and functional data in Djuretic et al. (2007) (Fig 2 and 3).

Activated by STAT4: functional data in Afkarian et al. (2002) (Fig 3A); binding data in Balasubramani et al. (2010) (Fig 4B and S4).

Activated by NFAT: functional data in Kiani et al. (2001) (Fig 1).

Activated by IL18R: functional data in Blom and Poulsen (2012) (Fig 2A).

Inhibited by FOXP3: functional data in Bettelli et al. (2005) (Fig 1).

Foxp3 represses IFNgt activation by NFAT (Bettelli et al., 2005). Foxp3 directly binds to NFAT (Bettelli et al., 2005).

Tbet and Runx3 cooperate to activate IFNgt (Djuretic et al, 2007).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="242" y="436" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL4" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="NFAT &amp; proliferation &amp; GATA3 &amp; (STAT5 | cMAF) &amp; !FOXP3 &amp; !((TBET &amp; RUNX3) | IRF1)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6014"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 4.

Interleukin 4 is produced by Th2 cells.

Activated by Gata3: functional data in Ouyang et al. (2000) (Fig 5A); binding data in Agarwal et al. (2000) (Fig 7).

Activated by NFAT: functional data in Bettelli et al. (2005) (Fig 3A).

Activated by Stat5: functional and binding data in Zhu et al. (2003) (Fig 1 and 7).

Activated by cMAF: functional data in Nurieva et al. (2003) (Fig 3C).

Inhibited by Foxp3: functional data in Bettelli et al. (2005) (Fig 1B).

Inhibited by Tbet and Runx3: functional and binding data in Djuretic et al. (2007) (Fig 5A and 7).

Inhibited by Irf1: functional and binding data in Elser et al. (2002) (Fig 3 and Table 1).

Foxp3 represses IL4 activation by NFAT (Bettelli et al., 2005). Foxp3 directly binds to NFAT (Bettelli et al., 2005).

Tbet and Runx3 cooperate to inhibit IL4 (Djuretic et al, 2007).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="929" y="446" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(NFAT | NFKB) &amp; !TBET &amp; !FOXP3 &amp; !(STAT5 &amp; STAT6)"/>
        <exp str="NFAT &amp; TBET &amp; !FOXP3 &amp; !(STAT5 &amp; STAT6)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6001"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 2.

Activated by NFKB: binding and functional data in Hwang et al. (2005a) (Fig 6 and 7).

Activated by NFAT: functional data in Peng et al. (2001) (Fig 2C).

Inhibited by Foxp3: functional data in Bettelli et al. (2005) (Fig 1A).

Inhibited by Tbet: binding and functional data in Hwang et al. (2005a) (Fig 6).

Inhibited by Stat5: functional data in Villarino et al. (2007) (Fig 3).

Inhibited by Stat6: functional data in Villarino et al. (2007) (Fig 4).

Foxp3 represses IL2 activation by NFAT and NFkb (Bettelli et al., 2005). Foxp3 directly binds to NFAT and NFkb (Bettelli et al., 2005). 

According to (Villarino et al, 2007, Fig 3A, 3B, 4C and 4D), in IL4 activating conditions, STAT5 and STAT6 cooperate to inhibit IL2 production.

According to (Hwang et al, 2005), Tbet inhibits the activation of IL2 by relA (a NFkB subunits) through heterodimerization.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1075" y="447" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL17" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="NFAT &amp; proliferation &amp; RORGT &amp; NFKB &amp; STAT3 &amp; !(FOXP3 &amp; STAT1 &amp; STAT5 &amp; STAT6)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5981"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:16404"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 17.

Interleukin 17 is produced by Th17 cells.

Activated by Rorgt: functional data in Ivanov et al. (2006) (Fig 3A).

Activated by Stat3: functional and binding data in Chen et al. (2006) (Fig 3E) and Laurence et al. (2007) (Fig 4A).

Inhibited by Stat5: functional and binding data in Laurence et al. (2007) (Fig 5 and 6).

Inhibited by Foxp3: functional data in Zhou et al. (2008) (Fig 3C).

IL4 (which activates Stat6) and IFNg and IL27 (which activate Stat1) inhibit IL17 production (Batten et al. (2006) (Fig 2a); Harrington et al. (2005); Stumhofer et al. (2006) (Fig 4, 5)). We assume that Stat1 and Stat6 inhibit IL17 to account for these observations (binding data in Laurence et al. (2007)).

We assume that NFKB activates IL17.

Foxp3 interacts with RORct and inhibits RORct-directed IL-17 expression (Zhou et al., 2008).

IL17 is not expressed in STAT3 or RORgt deficient mice (Zhou et al., 2007, Fig.5A and 3B) which suggest a cooperative activation by STAT3 and RORGT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1189" y="447" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL22" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="proliferation &amp; NFAT &amp; (STAT3 | STAT1) &amp; !cMAF"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:14900"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 22.

Activated by Stat3: functional data in Yang et al. (2007) (Fig 2D and 3C).

Inhibited by cMAF: functional and binding data in Rutz et al. (2011) (Fig 3, 4, 7 and 8).

We assume that Stat1 activates IL22 in order to reproduce IL22 production in environmental condition with IL12 (Volpe et al. (2008), Fig 5A).

We assume that IL22 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="384" y="440" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL9" name="IL9" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(NFKB | NFAT) &amp; proliferation &amp; (SMAD3 | PU1 | IL33R) &amp; STAT6"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6029"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 9.

Activated by NFKB: functional and binding data in Jash et al. (2012) (Fig 5, 6 and 7).

Activated by IL33R: functional data in Blom et al. (2011) (Fig 5).

Activated by Stat6: functional data in Veldhoen et al. (2008) (Fig 2A and 2C).

Activated by NFAT: functional and binding data in Jash et al. (2012) (Fig 2 and 3).

Activated by Smad3: functional and binding data in Elyaman et al. (2012) (Fig 4).

Activated by PU1: functional and binding data in Chang et al. (2010) (Fig 4 and 5).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="576" y="447" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL10" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(GATA3 | STAT3 | STAT4 | cMAF | IRF1) &amp; NFAT &amp; proliferation &amp; !IL18R &amp; !IL33R"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5962"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 10.

Activated by Gata3: functional data in Shoemaker et al. (2006) (Fig 2 and 4).

Activated by Stat3: functional data in Ziegler-Heitbrock et al. (2003) (Fig 6).

Activated by Stat4: functional data in Saraiva et al. (2009) (Fig 2A and 3).

Activated by cMAF: functional and binding data in Xu et al. (2009) (Fig 5 and 6).

Inhibited by IL18R and IL33R: functional data in Blom and Poulsen (2012) (Fig 2A).

We assume that Irf1 activates IL10 (binding data in Ziegler-Heitbrock et al. (2003) (Fig 1)) in order to reproduce IL10 production in Th1 cells (Volpe et al. (2008)).

We assume that IL10 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="657" y="448" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL3" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="GATA3 &amp; proliferation &amp; NFAT"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6011"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 3.

Activated by Gata3 in Jurkat cells: functional data in Kitamura et al. (2005) (Fig 3).

We assume that IL3 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1005" y="447" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL21" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="NFAT &amp; proliferation &amp; (STAT3 | cMAF | STAT4)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6005"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 21.

Activated by Stat3: functional and binding data in  Durant et al. (2010) (Fig 4) and Zhou et al. (2007) (Fig 5B).

Activated by Stat4: functional data in Schmitt et al. (2009) (Fig 6).

Activated by cMAF: functional data in Bauquet et al. (2009) (Fig 6E).

We assume that IL21 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="467" y="443" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL5" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="proliferation &amp; NFAT &amp; (GATA3 | cMAF | IL33R) &amp; !FOXP3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6016"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 5.

Interleukin 5 is produced by Th2 cells.

Activated by Gata3: functional and binding data in Zhu et al (2004) (Fig 3A) and Zhang et al (1998) (Fig 4B).

Activated by IL33R: functional data in Kurowska-Stolarska et al. (2008) (Fig 1C).

Activated by cMAF: functional data in Nurieva et al. (2003) (Fig 3C).

Inhibited by Foxp3: functional data in Dardalhon et al. (2008) (Fig 3D).

We assume that IL5 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="792" y="445" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL13" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="proliferation &amp; NFAT &amp; (GATA3 | cMAF | IL33R) &amp; !FOXP3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5973"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 13.

Interleukin 13 is produced by Th2 cells.

Activated by Gata3: functional and binding data in Zhu et al. (2004) (Fig 3) and Lavenu-Bombled et al. (2002) (Fig 6 and 7).

Activated by cMAF: functional data in Nurieva et al. (2003) (Fig 3C).

Activated by IL33R: functional data in Kurowska-Stolarska et al. (2008) (Fig 1C).

Inhibited by Foxp3: functional data in Dardalhon et al. (2008) (Fig 3C).

We assume that IL13 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="855" y="446" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL6" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="proliferation &amp; NFAT &amp; STAT3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6018"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 6.

We assume that Stat3 activates IL6 in order to reproduce IL6 production in Th17 polarizing condition (Volpe et al. (2008)).

We assume that IL6 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="322" y="441" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="STAT1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IFNAR | IFNGR | IL27R"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11362"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Stat1.

Activated by IL27R: functional data in Kamiya et al. (2004) (Fig 1).

Activated by IFNAR and IFNGR: functional data in Kotenko and Pestka (2000) and Horvath et al. (1995) (Fig 4).

</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="186" y="338" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="STAT3" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IL6R | IL23R | IL1R | IL21R | IL27R"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11364"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Stat3.

Activated by IL10R: functional data in Finbloom and Winestock (1995) (Fig 5).

Activated by IL23R: functional data in Parham et al. (2002) (Fig 6A).

Activated by IL6R: functional data in Croker et al. (2003) (Fig 3D).

Activated by IL27R: functional data in Charlot-Rabiega et al. (2011) (Fig 4A).

Activated by IL21R: functional data in Brenne et al. (2002) (Fig 7).

Activated by IL1R: functional data in Maitra et al. (2009) (Fig 4).






</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="508" y="330" style="Node style 17"/>
    </node>
    <node id="STAT4" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IL12R &amp; !GATA3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11365"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Stat4.

Activated by IL12R: functional data in Rogge et al. (1998) (Fig 4A).

Inhibited by Gata3: functional data in Usui et al. (2003) (Fig 1).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="815" y="334" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="STAT5" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="IL2R:2"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!IL2R:2 &amp; (IL2R:1 | IL15R)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11366"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11367"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Stat5.

Activated by IL2R: functional data in Chen et al. (2006) (Fig 3C).

Activated by IL15R: functional data in Pandiyan et al. (2012) (Fig 5).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="978" y="334" style="Node style 18"/>
    </node>
    <node id="STAT6" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IL4R"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11368"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Stat6.

Activated by IL4R: functional data in Chen et al. (2006) (Fig 3B).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="874" y="337" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="cMAF" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="TGFBR &amp; STAT3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6776"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor c-Maf.

Activated by TGFBR and Stat3: functional data in Xu et al. (2009) (Fig 1B).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="670" y="336" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="PU1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="TGFBR"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11241"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor PU.1.

PU.1 is specific to Th9 lineage.

Activated by TGFBR: funtional data in Chang et al. (2010) (Fig 1D).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="746" y="338" style="Node style 17"/>
    </node>
    <node id="TGFB" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="NFAT &amp; proliferation &amp; FOXP3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11766"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transformin growth factor, beta.

Transformin growth factor beta is produced by Treg cells.

We assume that TGFB is activated by Foxp3 to account for TGFB production by Treg cells (Vignali et al. (2008)).

We assume that TGFB production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="735" y="448" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="SMAD3" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="TGFBR"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6769"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Smad3.

Activated by TGFBR: functional data in Yang et al. (1999).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="762" y="580" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IRF1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="STAT1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:6116"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Irf1.

We assume that Irf1 is activated by Stat1 to account for IRF1 activation by IFNg signaling (Kano et al. (2008), Fig 2D).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="323" y="644" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="RUNX3" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="TBET"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:10473"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor Runx3.

Activated by Tbet: functional data in Djuretic et al. (2007) (Fig 1).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="64" y="690" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="proliferation" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="STAT5:2 | proliferation"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <comment>This component denotes cell proliferation. 
It is used as a switch required for the expression of most cytokines.

Activated by Stat5: functional data in Moriggl et al. (1999) (Fig 3). </comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1171" y="39" style="Node style 16"/>
    </node>
    <node id="NFKB" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!IKB &amp; !FOXP3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:7794"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:7795"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:9955"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:9956"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:9954"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor NF-kB.

The mammalian NF-kB family is composed of  NF-kB1, NF-kB2, RelA, RelB and c-Rel.

Inhibited by Foxp3: binding and functional data in Bettelli et al. (2005) (Fig 2, 3 and 4).

Inhibited by IKB: binding and functional data in Weil and Israel (2006).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1734" y="401" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="NFAT" name="NFAT" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="TCR &amp; CD28"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:7775"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:7776"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:7777"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:7778"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Transcription factor NFAT.

The NFAT family is composed of NFATc1, NFATc2, NFATc3, NFATc4 and NFATc5. The nucleus localisation of NFATc1 to NFATc4 depends on TCR activation.

Activated by TCR and CD28: functional data in Diehn et al. (2002).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1653" y="401" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IKB" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!TCR"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:7797"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Protein IkappaB.

Inhibited by TCR: functional data in Weil and Israel (2006).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1760" y="311" style="Node style 9"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL31" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="NFAT &amp; proliferation &amp; STAT6"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:19372"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 31.

Activated by Stat6: functional and binding data in Park et al. (2012) (Fig 5, 7 and 8).

Activated by NFAT: functional and binding data in Park et al. (2012) (Fig 5 and 6).

Stat6 and NFAT activate IL31 in a synergistic manner (Park et al., 2012).</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1461" y="448" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL25" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="NFAT &amp; proliferation &amp; GATA3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:13765"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 25.

We assume that Gata3 activates IL25 in order to reproduce IL25 production in Th2 cells (Paul and Zhu (2010)).

We assume that IL25 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1381" y="446" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL35" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="NFAT &amp; proliferation &amp; FOXP3"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:3129"/>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:5969"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 35.
Heterodimer IL12A-EBI3

Interleukin 35 is produced by Treg cells.

Activated by Foxp3: functional data in Collison et al. (2007) (Fig S5B).

We assume that IL35 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1282" y="447" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IL24" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="NFAT &amp; proliferation &amp; STAT6"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="hugo:11346"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Interleukin 24.

Activated by Stat6: functional and binding data in Sahoo et al. (2011) (Fig 5, 6 and 8).

We assume that IL24 production requires NFAT.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1555" y="446" style="Node style 24"/>
    </node>
